[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Solid Fuel Association (HOT03)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The Solid Fuel Association is the organisation which represents the producers, distributors, retailers and manufacturers of the British domestic solid fuel sector
[normal] including wood fuel
[normal] producers
[normal]. We provide consumer guidance and technical support for installers, other industry professionals and the general public. 
[normal]The SFA also administer the Approved Coal Merchant Scheme in accordance with the requirements of Tradin
[normal]g Standards and in this capacity work very closely with the Coal Merchants Federation.
[normal]We have recently launched the Approved Woodfuel Merchant Scheme to protect consumers in this rapidly growing sector of the solid fuel industry.
[normal]Coal mining
[normal] itself
[normal] is wor
[normal]th around £1 billion to the UK economy. 
[normal]Around 
[normal]5
[normal],000 British people are employed directly in the industry and at least another 20,000 are dependent on the various support industries around coal for their living. Many of this number are in areas that are a
[normal]lready economically disadvantaged.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Summary[bold]The SFA 
[normal]believe
[normal] that the 
[normal]true value of coal to the UK
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]including
[normal] its potential 
[normal]contribution to the
[normal] domestic sector
[normal],
[normal] is currently being completely 
[normal]disregarded
[normal].
[normal]Recent initiatives from government and in particular the Green Deal seem to completely 
[normal]dismiss
[normal] the
[normal] benefits of solid fuel heating. There is a dichotomy at the heart of government policy which sets solid fuels
[normal] apart 
[normal]from other fossil fuels
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We have set out
[normal] below in simple terms what our industry has to offer 
[normal]in terms of economy, security and sustainability 
[normal]and why coal 
[normal]has 
[normal]all 
[normal]the credentials to be a fuel of the future.
[normal]&#xa0;
